OOPS! Studio! 2023-05-01 9:37 PM
Floating point errors are tiny errors in the way floating point numbers are stored in memory. For the sake of saving memory, computers won't store exact values, but rather they'll truncate it to a certain level of precision. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_arithmetic (edited)
9:38 PM
And if that truncation happens too much, the results can be wildly inaccurate
OOPS! Studio!

OOPS! Studio! 2023-05-01 9:40 PM
It has to do with the binary representation of floating point numbers.
9:40 PM
For integers (whole numbers), the computer will store the values using the standard binary system
9:40 PM
But for floating point numbers, they are much more complex, and so people have invented all different means of storing them
OOPS! Studio!
But for floating point numbers, they are much more complex, and so people have invented all different means of storing them
rher 2023-05-01 9:41 PM
ah i get it now
OOPS! Studio! 2023-05-01 9:41 PM
They do this because the only other "fully accurate" way of storing them would be to store each individual digit as its own 4-bit number
9:41 PM
Which would consume tons of memory (edited)
9:41 PM
So people come up with these much more compact ways to store floating point numbers, and the tradeoff is that they are not fully accurate
